          "body": "After Saul leaves the cave, David follows and calls out to him (24:8) — an act requiring extraordinary courage, since Saul has 3,000 men and David's position is now exposed. David bows to the ground (24:8), a posture of submission to the king whose life he just spared. His speech (24:9-15) is a masterpiece of forensic rhetoric. He first identifies the source of the problem: 'Why do you listen to the words of men?' (24:9) — slander has driven Saul's campaign, not David's actual conduct. He then presents the evidence: the robe hem in his hand (24:11), the fact that he was counseled to kill and refused (24:10). He makes a clear moral claim: 'there is no evil or rebellion in my hands, and I have not sinned against you, though you are lying in wait for my life' (24:11). The contrast in 24:11 is stark — David names what Saul is doing ('lying in wait for my life') even while denying that he himself has done anything comparable. He then invokes the ancient proverb (24:13): 'Out of the wicked comes forth wickedness' — a mirror held before Saul without naming him directly. His closing appeal (24:12, 15) is to the LORD as judge, vindicator, and deliverer. David does not ask Saul to stop; he asks God to adjudicate. The speech ends with utter self-abasement: 'a dead dog, a single flea' (24:14) — David describes himself in the lowest possible terms to make the absurdity of the royal pursuit visible."
