          "title": "The closing irony: David back to the stronghold",
          "body": "The chapter's final verse (24:22) is deliberately anticlimactic. Saul went home; David and his men went up to the stronghold. The emotional catharsis of verses 16-21 has resolved nothing in David's external circumstances. He is still a fugitive. The confession has not produced Saul's abdication. The oath is a moral victory, not a political one. This is the chapter's honest eschatology: doing the right thing does not immediately change your situation. David committed his cause to the LORD (24:12, 15) and received a verbal vindication — but the vindication came in words, not in a throne. He returns to the stronghold just as he left it. This ending is not a failure of the narrative; it is its integrity. The chapter argues that the believer who entrusts vengeance to God will be vindicated — but vindication comes on God's timetable, not the moment moral rightness is demonstrated. The stronghold David goes back to is both a fortress and a figure: his security rests not in his vindication by Saul but in the LORD who will eventually establish the kingdom in his hand (24:20)."
